{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1769467993,"nonce":"6FbTiKFtOb6pbpvU6LCRdmvqCy0=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87l9K6n","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/45","origin":"github"},"title":"Protocol: Standardize GitHub Issues as Single Source of Truth","message":"# Goal\nMake GitHub Issues the core tracking mechanism for all agent tasks, as defined in `PROPOSAL_MULTI_AGENT_WORKFLOW.md`.\n\n# Context\nCurrently, agents accept tasks from the user without verifying if they are tracked in the backlog. This leads to untracked work and loss of context (Memory Architecture Layer 1).\n\n# Policy\n**Rule**: For any user request that implies a task (feature, bugfix, refactor) that is not already tracked by an issue, the agent **MUST** suggest creating an issue to the user.\n\n# Implementation Plan\n\n## 1. Update `AGENT_ONBOARDING.md`\nAdd a new step before 'Create a Feature Branch':\n\u003e **3. Ticket the Task**\n\u003e *   Check if a GitHub Issue exists for your current objective.\n\u003e *   If not, ask the user: 'Should I open an issue to track this?'\n\u003e *   Naming convention for branch becomes: `feature/ISSUE-\u003cID\u003e-\u003cdescription\u003e` (aligning with issue ID).\n\n## 2. New Rule: `rules/common/issue-first.md`\nCreate a rule file that codifies this behavior:\n\u003e *   **No Code Without a Ticket**: Agents should not begin coding until an issue number is assigned, unless it is a trivial 'drive-by' fix.\n\u003e *   **Linkage**: The `implementation_plan.md` must link to the Issue.\n\n## 3. Update `PLANNING_MODE.md`\nUpdate the Planning Mode rule to include:\n\u003e *   **Prerequisite**: Ensure a GitHub Issue exists.\n\u003e *   **Output**: The `implementation_plan.md` should start with `Ref: Issue #123`.\n\n## 4. Leverage `issue-triage` Skill\nEncourage agents to use the `issue-triage` skill to quickly open tickets with correct labels.","files":null}]}